<paragraph blockId="16.[86,1042,1449,1696]" box="[86,256,1449,1473]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis box="[86,256,1449,1473]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">Related species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[86,1042,1449,1696]" lastBlockId="17.[86,1042,142,358]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="174" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
There are three other 
<taxonomicName box="[375,497,1481,1505]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="embadion">
<emphasis box="[375,497,1481,1505]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L embadion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (table 2), all easily distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esteban &amp; Finlay &amp; Olmo &amp; Tyler" authorityYear="2000" box="[86,226,1513,1536]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="curvatum">
<emphasis box="[86,226,1513,1536]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L. curvatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
through the observation of living organisms. 
<taxonomicName box="[769,969,1513,1537]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="subSpecies" species="embadion" subSpecies="lucens">
<emphasis box="[769,969,1513,1537]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L embadion lucens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest species, rarely larger than 
<quantity box="[491,536,1545,1569]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="60.0">
60 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[522,536,1545,1569]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">m</emphasis>
</quantity>
m, a characteristic that makes identi®cation straightforward. This ciliate is a common freshwater organism, ellipsoidal in shape and ¯attened, found amongst sediment particles. 
<emphasis box="[674,902,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
<taxonomicName box="[674,797,1609,1633]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="embadion">L embadion</taxonomicName>
magnum
</emphasis>
is typically planktonic, ellipsoidal in shape, unmistakable because of its oral aperture (which is almost as long as the cell) and its method of capturing food particles which involves the ciliate swimming in a manner that resembles a rotating`baseball glove’. 
<taxonomicName box="[86,311,174,198]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="subSpecies" species="embadion" subSpecies="bullinum">
<emphasis box="[86,311,174,198]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L embadion bullinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also ellipsoidal, and it is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[721,843,174,198]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="embadion">
<emphasis box="[721,843,174,198]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L embadion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species described so far with cell dimorphism, i.e. it is able to form cannibal giants (
<bibRefCitation author="KUHLMANN, H. - W." box="[833,1023,206,230]" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" pagination="336" refId="ref13169" refString="KUHLMANN, H. - W., 1993, Giants in L embadion bullinum (Ciliophora, Hymenostomata) D general morphology and inducing conditions, Archiv fuEr Protistenkunde, 143, 325 ± 336." type="journal article" year="1993">Kuhlmann, 1993</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esteban &amp; Finlay &amp; Olmo &amp; Tyler" authorityYear="2000" box="[86,322,237,261]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="subSpecies" species="embadion" subSpecies="curvatum">
<emphasis box="[86,322,237,261]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L embadion curvatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[468,590,237,261]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="embadion">
<emphasis box="[468,590,237,261]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L embadion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a twisted, curved, C-shaped cell. Other morphological distinguishing features of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esteban &amp; Finlay &amp; Olmo &amp; Tyler" authorityYear="2000" box="[657,801,270,293]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="species" species="curvatum">
<emphasis box="[657,801,270,293]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L. curvatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the number of somatic kineties and the cell size. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esteban &amp; Finlay &amp; Olmo &amp; Tyler" authorityYear="2000" box="[490,726,301,325]" class="Oligohymenophorea" family="Lembadionidae" genus="Lembadion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Hymenostomatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="174" phylum="Ciliophora" rank="subSpecies" species="embadion" subSpecies="curvatum">
<emphasis box="[490,726,301,325]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="174">L embadion curvatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a benthic ciliate, and is always observed among sediment particles.
</paragraph>
